The `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header is used in CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) requests to allow resources from one domain to be accessed by another domain. When this header is set to `*` or a wildcard, it means that any origin (domain) is allowed to access the resource, which is a common practice for development and testing purposes.

However, when you make a request using Fetch API, the browser sends the `Authorization` header automatically only if it has already been included in the same-origin requests. This means that if your server responds with an `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`, it does not necessarily mean that your authorization headers will be ignored.

In order to send authorization headers with your Fetch API request, you need to include them explicitly in the options object passed to the `fetch()` method. Here's an example:

```js
const token = "Bearer YOUR_TOKEN";

fetch("https://example.com/api", {
  headers: {
    Authorization: token
  }
})
.then(response => response.json())
.then(data => console.log(data))
.catch(error => console.error(error));
```

In this example, we're including the authorization header in the options object passed to the `fetch()` method, with the value of our bearer token. Make sure to replace `YOUR_TOKEN` with your actual access token.

So, to answer your question, setting `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` to `*` or a wildcard should not prevent you from sending authorization headers with your Fetch API request. Just remember to include them explicitly in the options object passed to the `fetch()` method.

